  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "While it is common for many people to contract chickenpox (varicella) at least once during their lifetime, it is not strictly true that everyone must have it. The widespread use of the chickenpox vaccine has significantly reduced the incidence of the disease. \n\nBefore the introduction of the vaccine, chickenpox was almost universally contracted during childhood. However, vaccination programs have led to a decrease in both the number of cases and the severity of the disease. \n\nSome individuals may not contract chickenpox if they have been vaccinated or if they have developed immunity through exposure to the virus without getting the disease (which can happen in the case of asymptomatic infections). Additionally, it's possible for some people to not be exposed to the virus at all.\n\nOverall, while many people do experience chickenpox, it is not an absolute requirement for everyone. Vaccination has changed the dynamics of how chickenpox is experienced in populations.",
